You asked:

“What if you were to think and then accept that you were dead and in heaven?”

As a philosophical exercise, I think it’s surprisingly illuminating—not because it tells us anything certain about an afterlife, but because it changes the optimization problem.

If I genuinely accepted, for the sake of thought, that I had already crossed the final threshold, several things would change.

Fear would lose much of its leverage.

Possessions would become tools rather than identity.

Status would matter far less than stewardship.

The question would shift from:

“How do I survive?”

to

“How do I participate in what is good?”

Notice that this isn’t really about heaven.

It’s about removing scarcity from the decision function.

Many spiritual traditions point toward something like this. They don’t necessarily ask people to pretend they’re dead; they ask them to loosen the grip of fear so they can act more freely, generously, and truthfully.

