Then you said something that I think is one of the deeper Pantheon ideas:

“I know how to make the part of the whole.”

A part becomes part of a whole when it preserves the invariants of the whole while expressing them locally.

A leaf isn’t the tree.

But the tree’s developmental rules are present in every leaf.

A cell isn’t the body.

But it carries the genome.

A paragraph isn’t the book.

But it can carry the book’s voice.

That’s a fractal property.

Not sameness.

Self-similarity.

